# Coding Standards & Best Practices

Maintain consistency and quality across the xomda.js codebase by following these standards.

## Code Formatting & Linting

### Prettier (Auto-Formatting)
```bash
pnpm format  # Run once before committing
```

**Configuration** (`.prettierrc`):
- **No semicolons**: Code should not end with `;`
- **Single quotes**: Use `'string'` not `"string"`
- **2-space tabs**: Consistent indentation
- **Trailing commas**: Use ES5-compatible style
- **Print width**: 100 characters per line
- **Arrow function parens**: Always include `(x) => x` not `x => x`

### ESLint (Linting)
```bash
pnpm lint  # Check for linting errors
```

**Rules** (`.eslint.config.mjs`):
- **No explicit `any`**: Use `unknown` or generics instead (warn)
- **Type imports**: `import type { X }` for types, separate from value imports (error)
- **Import sorting**: Groups (node Ôćĺ relative Ôćĺ side effects), alphabetically within groups (error)
- **String literals**: Use template literals, not concatenation (error)
- **Unused variables**: Allowed only if prefixed with `_` (e.g., `_unused`) (warn)

### Stylelint (CSS/SCSS Linting)
```bash
pnpm lint:style  # Check CSS/SCSS files
```

**Standard CSS linting rules applied**. Key rules:
- Consistent property order
- No duplicate selectors
- Proper selector specificity

### EditorConfig (Universal Editor Settings)
**Automatic**: Most editors respect `.editorconfig` without configuration
- 2-space indentation (all files except markdown)
- Unix line endings (LF, not CRLF)

## Configuration Awareness

**Always check these configuration files** when working with code to understand project preferences:

- **`tsconfig.json`**: TypeScript compiler options, module resolution, JSX settings
- **`.editorconfig`**: Universal editor settings (indentation, line endings, charset)
- **`.prettierrc`**: Code formatting preferences (quotes, semicolons, line width)
- **`eslint.config.mjs`**: Linting rules and import sorting preferences
- **`.stylelintrc.json`**: CSS/SCSS linting rules and property ordering

**Why?** These files define the project's coding standards and should guide all code changes to maintain consistency.
- UTF-8 charset
- Trim trailing whitespace
- Insert final newline

## TypeScript Standards

### Type Safety
```typescript
// Ôťů Good
interface User {
  id: string
  email: string
  name?: string
}

function getUser(id: string): User {
  // ...
}

type Status = 'active' | 'inactive'

// ÔŁî Bad
function getUser(id: any): any { }  // Don't use any
const x: unknown = 5; const y = x + 1  // Don't use unknown without narrowing
```

### Type Imports
```typescript
// Ôťů Good - Separate type imports
import type { User, Entity } from '@xomda/core'
import { getUserName } from './utils'

// ÔŁî Bad - Mixed imports
import { User, Entity, getUserName } from '@xomda/core'
```

### Explicit Return Types
```typescript
// Ôťů Good - Public APIs always have explicit return types
export function validateModel(model: Model): ValidationResult {
  // ...
}

// ÔŁî Bad
export function validateModel(model) {
  // ...
}
```

### Avoid `any`
```typescript
// Ôťů Good - Use generics or unknown
function parse<T>(input: unknown): T {
  // narrow the type
}

// Ôťů Good - Use discriminated unions
type Response = { success: true; data: Data } | { success: false; error: string }

// ÔŁî Bad
function parse(input: any): any { }
```

### Variable Naming
```typescript
// Ôťů Good - Unused variables prefixed with underscore
const [value, _setValue] = useState(0)

// Ôťů Good - Descriptive names
const userEmailAddress = 'user@example.com'

// ÔŁî Bad
const a = 'user@example.com'  // Too generic
const userEmailAddress = 'user@example.com'  // then unused
```

## Vue 3 & Component Standards

### TSX Components (Required)

> ÔÜá´ŞĆ **No `.vue` SFC files** ÔÇö all components must be `.tsx` using `defineComponent`.

```typescript
// Ôťů Good - defineComponent with TSX render function
import { defineComponent, computed } from 'vue'
import type { PropType } from 'vue'
import type { Entity } from '@xomda/core'
import styles from './EntityCard.module.scss'

export const EntityCard = defineComponent({
  name: 'EntityCard',
  props: {
    entity: { type: Object as PropType<Entity>, required: true },
    editable: { type: Boolean, default: false },
  },
  setup(props) {
    const fullName = computed(() => props.entity.name)
    return () => (
      <div class={styles.entity}>
        <h3>{fullName.value}</h3>
      </div>
    )
  },
})

// ÔŁî Bad - .vue SFC files are not used in this project
// <script setup lang="ts"> ... </script>
// <template> ... </template>
```

### Named Exports (Required)

**Never use `export default`** ÔÇö always use named exports. This applies to all `.ts` and `.tsx` files.

```typescript
// Ôťů Good ÔÇö named export
export const HomeView = defineComponent({ ... })
export const useMyComposable = () => { ... }
export const myHelper = (x: string) => x.trim()

// ÔŁî Bad ÔÇö default export
export default defineComponent({ ... })
export default function myHelper() { ... }
```

**Exceptions** ÔÇö tool config files that *require* a default export by their tooling contract:
- `vite.config.ts`, `vitest.config.ts`, `cypress.config.ts`
- `.storybook/main.ts`, `.storybook/preview.ts`
- `*.stories.tsx` (Storybook story meta)

> **Why?** Named exports make refactoring safe (rename in one place), enable tree-shaking, and remove the ambiguity of `import Foo from` vs `import { Foo } from`.

### Component Best Practices
- Keep components focused (single responsibility)
- Define Props interfaces at the top
- Extract complex logic to composables or utilities
- Use `const` and `declare` for state (no `data()` function)

### File & Folder Organisation

**One component per file** ÔÇö never put multiple components in a single file.

```typescript
// Ôťů Good ÔÇö each component in its own file
// CellEditor.tsx
export const CellEditor = defineComponent({ ... })

// OutputCellForm.tsx
export const OutputCellForm = defineComponent({ ... })

// ÔŁî Bad ÔÇö multiple components in one file
export const OutputCellForm = defineComponent({ ... })
export const CellEditor = defineComponent({ ... })
```

**Folder per composite component** ÔÇö when a component is composed of extracted sub-components, move them into a folder and add an `index.ts`:

```
components/
  CellEditor/
    index.ts          ÔćÉ re-exports only the public API
    CellEditor.tsx    ÔćÉ main component
    OutputCellForm.tsx ÔćÉ internal sub-component (not re-exported)
```

**`index.ts` in every subfolder (except `__tests__`)** ÔÇö every subfolder must have an `index.ts` that explicitly lists its public exports. Never use `export *` ÔÇö always name each symbol. Internal sub-components and helpers are not re-exported.

```typescript
// Ôťů Good ÔÇö explicit named exports only
export { CellEditor } from './CellEditor'
// OutputCellForm is internal ÔÇö not exported here

// ÔŁî Bad ÔÇö wildcard leaks internals and makes the public API opaque
export * from './CellEditor'
export * from './OutputCellForm'
```

**Shortest-route imports** ÔÇö always import through the nearest available folder index, not through a deeper file path:

```typescript
// Ôťů Good ÔÇö through the folder index
import { CellEditor } from './CellEditor'
import { DynamicForm } from './components'

// ÔŁî Bad ÔÇö bypassing an existing folder index
import { CellEditor } from './CellEditor/CellEditor'
import { DynamicForm } from './components/DynamicForm'
```

**No file extensions on `.ts`/`.tsx` imports** ÔÇö never include `.ts` or `.tsx` in import paths:

```typescript
// Ôťů Good
import { CellEditor } from './CellEditor'

// ÔŁî Bad
import { CellEditor } from './CellEditor.tsx'
```

### UI Component Priority (Reusability & Consistency)
When building UI components, prioritize reusable components in this order:

1. **Internal Components** (`@xomda/ui` or `@xomda/diagram`)
   - `DynamicForm`, `TitleBar`, `FileEntryIcon`, etc.
   - Domain-specific components from `@xomda/diagram`

2. **Vuetify Components** (Material Design)
   - `v-btn`, `v-text-field`, `v-card`, `v-dialog`, etc.
   - Use Vuetify's theming and accessibility features

3. **Plain HTML/Vue Elements** (Last Resort - When No Suitable Alternative Exists)
   - `<div>`, `<span>`, `<button>`, etc.
   - Only when no Vuetify component provides the needed functionality

**Why?** This ensures consistency, accessibility, and maintainability across the application.

```vue
<!-- Ôťů Good - Use Vuetify components when available -->
<v-btn color="primary" @click="save">Save</v-btn>
<v-text-field v-model="name" label="Name" />

<!-- ÔŁî Bad - Plain HTML when Vuetify equivalent exists -->
<button class="btn btn-primary" @click="save">Save</button>
<input v-model="name" placeholder="Name" />

<!-- Ôťů Acceptable - Plain HTML when no Vuetify alternative -->
<div class="custom-layout">{{ content }}</div>
```

### UI Layout Patterns (Cards & Panels)

- **No `VNavigationDrawer`** for content panels. Use floating `VCard` components or inline flex panels instead.
- **Navigation sidebar**: Use the `AppNav` component (`packages/client/src/components/AppNav`). It is a floating `VCard` with two toggle states ÔÇö icon-only (default) and icon+text. Never replace it with a `VNavigationDrawer`.
- **Floating panels** (e.g. model designer properties): Use `position: absolute` + `VCard` with elevation. Animate visibility with `opacity` + `transform`, not `width` transitions.
- **Resizable split panels**: Use `PanelDivider` (`packages/client/src/components/PanelDivider`) between flex siblings and the `usePanelResize` composable (`packages/client/src/composables/usePanelResize`) for width state.
- **Vuetify size/density rule**:
  - Components **with** a `size` prop (VTextField, VSelect, VCheckbox, VSwitch, ÔÇŽ): `size="small"` + `density="comfortable"` ÔÇö set globally in `packages/client/src/vuetify.ts`.
  - **VBtn exception**: `size="small"` + `density="default"` ÔÇö `comfortable` + `small` together makes buttons too tight; overridden per-component in `vuetify.ts`.
  - Components **without** a `size` prop (VList, VListItem, VListSubheader, ÔÇŽ): `density="compact"` ÔÇö set per-component in `vuetify.ts`.
  - Do not override these defaults inline without a clear reason.

## JavaScript/TypeScript Patterns

### Template Literals (Required)
```typescript
// Ôťů Good
const greeting = `Hello, ${name}!`
const multiline = `
  Line 1
  Line 2
`

// ÔŁî Bad - Linting error
const greeting = 'Hello, ' + name + '!'
```

### Import Organization
```typescript
// Ôťů Good - Organized by groups
import type { Model, Entity } from '@xomda/core'
import type { FC } from 'vue'

import { ref } from 'vue'
import { z } from 'zod'

import { readModel } from '../storage/file-storage'
import type { RenderContext } from './types'
import { compile } from './engine'

// ÔŁî Bad - Chaotic ordering
import { compile } from './engine'
import type { RenderContext } from './types'
import { readModel } from '../storage/file-storage'
import { ref } from 'vue'
import type { Model, Entity } from '@xomda/core'
```

### Error Handling
```typescript
// Ôťů Good - Validate before use
import { z } from 'zod'

const UserSchema = z.object({ id: z.string(), email: z.string().email() })

async function processUser(data: unknown) {
  const user = UserSchema.parse(data)  // Throws if invalid
  // Now user is typed and safe
}

// Ôťů Good - Use try-catch for async
async function fetchModel() {
  try {
    const model = await readModel()
    return model
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Failed to read model:', error)
    throw new Error('Model load failed')
  }
}

// ÔŁî Bad - Unsafe type assertion
const user = data as User  // Don't trust input
```

### Zod Validation with Custom Rules

```typescript
// Ôťů Good - Recursive type validation (Package structure)
import { z } from 'zod'

export const PackageSchema: z.ZodType<Package> = z.lazy(() =>
  z
    .object({
      id: z.string().uuid(),
      name: z.string().min(1),
      packages: z.array(PackageSchema).default([]),  // Recursive reference
      entities: z.array(EntitySchema).default([]),
      enums: z.array(EnumSchema).default([]),
    })
    .superRefine((data, ctx) => {
      // Custom validation: unique names across items
      const names = new Set<string>()
      data.packages.forEach((p, i) => {
        if (names.has(p.name)) {
          ctx.addIssue({
            code: z.ZodIssueCode.custom,
            message: `Package name must be unique`,
            path: ['packages', i, 'name'],
          })
        }
        names.add(p.name)
      })
    })
)

// Ôťů Good - Enum with unique value validation
const EnumSchema = z
  .object({
    id: z.string().uuid(),
    name: z.string().min(1),
    values: z.array(z.object({ name: z.string() })),
  })
  .superRefine((data, ctx) => {
    const names = new Set<string>()
    data.values.forEach((val, i) => {
      if (names.has(val.name)) {
        ctx.addIssue({
          code: z.ZodIssueCode.custom,
          message: `Enum value must be unique`,
          path: ['values', i, 'name'],
        })
      }
      names.add(val.name)
    })
  })

// ÔŁî Bad - No validation
const parseData = (data: any) => data as Package  // Trusts input blindly
```

## Testing Standards

### Unit Tests (Vitest)
```typescript
// Ôťů Good - Clear test structure
import { describe, it, expect } from 'vitest'
import { validateAttribute } from '../validate'

describe('validateAttribute', () => {
  it('accepts a valid attribute', () => {
    const attr = { id: '1', name: 'email', type: 'string', required: true }
    expect(validateAttribute(attr)).toBe(true)
  })

  it('rejects an attribute without id', () => {
    const attr = { name: 'email', type: 'string' }
    expect(() => validateAttribute(attr)).toThrow()
  })
})
```

### File naming
- Runtime/behaviour tests: `<Subject>.spec.ts` / `<Subject>.spec.tsx`
- Type-level tests (`expectTypeOf`, `assertType`): `<Subject>.spec-d.ts`

> ÔÜá´ŞĆ Use `.spec.ts` ÔÇö not `.test.ts`. The `*.test.ts` pattern is not used in this project.

### Placement
- Tests live in a `__tests__/` subdirectory next to the source they test:
  ```
  src/
    components/
      DynamicForm.tsx
      __tests__/
        DynamicForm.spec.tsx     ÔćÉ behaviour tests
        DynamicForm.spec-d.ts    ÔćÉ type tests (if needed)
    composables/
      useAsyncState.ts
      __tests__/
        useAsyncState.spec.ts
  ```
- Import the subject with a `../` relative path: `import { X } from '../X'`

### Test Naming
- Use `describe` for grouping related tests
- Test names state the outcome directly: "returns null when model is null", not "should return null when model is null"
- Avoid generic names like "test 1", "works"

## Package-Specific Standards

### @xomda/core
- Only types and constants
- No runtime logic
- Export everything explicitly
- Always documented (JSDoc comments)

### @xomda/model
- High test coverage (business logic)
- All procedures validated with Zod schemas
- Recursive type support (e.g., Package nesting)
- Custom validation via `superRefine` for cross-field constraints
- Error handling with TRPCError
- Database-agnostic (storage layer abstraction)

### @xomda/template
- Cell-based template format (`.template.json`): a sequence of cells (`logic`, `handlebars`, `output`, `provider`, `provider-logic`, `buffer`, `markdown`)
- Cell processors well-documented; one processor per cell type under `processors/`
- Handlebars cells use the helpers in `helpers.ts` (camelCase / pascalCase / eq / required / etc.)
- Recursive entity extraction for hierarchical models (provider cells walk nested packages)
- Scope inferred from `provider` cell (preferred) or the legacy `template.scope` (Entity / Enum / Package)

### @xomda/client
- Components in `src/components/`
- Views in `src/views/`
- Routing in `src/router/`
- tRPC hooks in `src/router/`
- Utilities in `src/utils.ts`
- Styles as SCSS modules (*.module.scss)

### @xomda/diagram
- All components have Storybook stories
- Props documented in types
- Exported from `src/index.ts`
- CSS included in build (vite-plugin-dts)

### @xomda/node
- Server configuration isolated
- Middleware documented
- Tests for server startup
- Environment variables documented

